metadata.name: Magic Board #123
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Journeys #18
metadata.description:
As #fxhashturnsone, it seemed apt to release one of my old WIPs, Journeys, to showcase my own journey in the creative coding space. The piece tries to recreate subway maps in a generative fashion, and is meant to reflect the journeys of people as they move and interact with each other. Some journey alongside each other before branching off, while others only meet at the end of their journeys. Even more will never meet at all.   

SAs #fxhashturnsone, it seemed apt to release one of my old WIPs, Journeys, to showcase my own journey in the creative coding space. The piece tries to recreate subway maps in a generative fashion, and is meant to reflect the journeys of people as they move and interact with each other. Some journey alongside each other before branching off, while others only meet at the end of their journeys. Even more will never meet at all.   

Several flow fields randomly determine the flow of each line, while attractors cause lines to be naturally drawn to certain places on the map. The code checks to ensure that lines do not overlap (but they can intersect!) and ensures a minimum distance between adjacent lines. Several code chunks are referenced in the comments which calculate intersections between points / lines.

THIS CODE IS VERY MUCH RAW AND UNFINISHED! It reflects my own growth in the space, where I started out, and where I'm heading towards. Happy birthday fxHash! I hope everyone finds their own Journey out there.

metadata.name: Landscapes out of my mind #126
metadata.description:
In this work, the third in the series of landscapes, I tried to achieve greater realism without abandoning those elements, also characteristic of the other works, which lead out of reality such as the shapes of the ground and trees and the choice of palettes.

Lands and Clouds are rendered using a mix of simplex noise and FBM (Fractional Brownian Motion), trees are generated with space colonization algorithm an placed using Poisson Disk Sampling distribution. The distribution density is driven by the land heightmap.


Developed with three.js using WebGLRenderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.


[s] to save a png at 2048x1536, 1536x2048, 2048x2048 (4/3, 3/4, 4/4 aspect ratio)
[d] to save a png at 4096x3072, 3072x4096, 4096x4096 (4/3, 3/4, 4/4 aspect ratio)


Features:
"Palette": 14 colormaps
"Aspect Ratio": 4/3, 3/4, 4/4
"View Point":  Far, Medium, Near, Above
"Sky Type": FBM, Gradient1, Gradient2
"Sky Color": LightSkyBlue, Gray, Blue [10% probability]
"Bark Color":  Brown, GrayBrown, Gray
"Bare Trees": True, False


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: CSS Molecules #73
metadata.description:
This 3d animated work is composed almost completely of HTML + CSS. There is a limited amount of javascript to construct the scene and facilitate interactive controls. 🚫 <canvas>!

A bit of history about this approach: As my first coding language HTML and CSS holds a special place in my heart. Even when I jumped into 3D my first creations were made with just some html + css coded in notepad. Earlier this year I took this idea to the next level with a yet-to-be-released 3D bedrooms project, filling it with objects and ever-refining my scene construction practice. This system for scene construction became the basis for a few other generative projects here on fxhash under my pseudonym htmlcss.tez. Here I abandon my usual representational focus with this technique and dive right into the abstract.

metadata.name: Alien Cities #113
metadata.description:
Alien Cities depicts fictional cities as they might look on another planet. Alien Cities are fractals, and can seem semi organic in nature. However, if you look close, you can see that each structure is sealed off from the atmosphere, showing its artificial nature.

Since Alien cities are a fractal, they have an almost infinite number of variations. In fact, taming the variability is one of the biggest challenges when using fractals. 

Alien Cities is coded using shaders, so it renders instantaneously on any size screen. The default view is gpu friendly, in that it will stop redrawing after a second or two. However, a gpu is recommended since it is a shader. See below about using the camera.

Variations:

- 22 hand tuned palettes.
- Fx, Fy, Fz control height and x/y spread of features.
- Angle controls the angles of the fractal folds. This has a large effect on the overall look of the city. If you get an angle close to a multiple of 90, the city will look much like a normal city block.
- Radius controls the size of the features in the fractal, and has a large effect on the height of the features.
- Being a fractal ensures all cities will be unique.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.

Camera:

If you add ?allowCamera=1 to the url after you open it in a separate browser window, you can use the camera. Note that this will constantly use gpu resources, as it is redrawing every frame. If you minimize the browser window, chrome is smart enough to stop rendering.

The camera is an orbit camera with the following controls:

- left mouse drag rotates the scene around the center.
- right mouse drag pans the scene (moves the center of the scene).
- mouse wheel zooms in and out.

Zooming out will show the entire city as an island floating in space. Zooming in will show the details of the fractal, which can be quite intricate.

metadata.name: fx(ornament) 2022 #436
metadata.description:
Tis the season to celebrate and what better way than with a collectible series of 2022 generative ornaments. Perfect for yourself or as gifts for people you love. 

Designed to be printed or plotted and then cut out and hung on your tree or any other place that needs a little festive cheer. 

I’ll be picking a few of my favorite outputs and sending the token owners special limited edition signed laser cut versions of their ornaments. 

———————

LIVE MODE FEATURES
- L prepares it for plotting or cutting
- S exports a layered SVG
- P exports a PNG
- 1-9 plays with color combos

———————

For years my family has collected Wallace Silver Candy Cane ornaments. Each Christmas the kids open up that years design and add it to the tree. With my daughters mostly grown, we now have quite the collection of dozens of ornaments from all the years. Each one full with memories and emotions. 

This series is inspired by that tradition, starting with 2022, and continuing with a new release each year. I hope you enjoy this series and it brings much delight and joy to you, your family, and friends this holiday season.
